'''Capetus''' or '''Capetus Silvius''' (said to have reigned 934-921 BC)<ref>[[Dionysius of Halicarnassus]] ''Roman Antiquities'' 1.71</ref>({{Lang-la|Căpĕtŭs Sĭluĭŭs}}) was a descendant of [[Aeneas]] and one of the legendary [[Latin kings of Alba Longa]]. He was the son of [[Capys]], and the father of [[Tiberinus Silvius|Tiberinus]], after whom the [[Tiber river]] was named. [[Geoffrey of Monmouth]] asserted in his ''[[Historia Regum Britanniae]]'' that Silvius (who he calls "Sylvius Epitus") succeeded Capys at the same time that [[Solomon]] began to build the [[Solomon's Temple|Temple in Jerusalem]] and was visited by the [[Queen of Sheba]], and king [[Leil]] of Britain founded [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]].<ref>{{cite wikisource|author=Geoffrey of Monmouth|authorlink=Geoffrey of Monmouth|others=Translation by Aaron Thompson, revised and corrected by [[John Allen Giles]]|wslink=History of the Kings of Britain/Book 2#9|title=History of the Kings of Britain|chapter=Book 2, chapter 9|year=1842|origyear=Written around 1136}}</ref>

