'''Dasakuta''' was one of two divisions (along with [[Vyasakuta]]) of [[Haridasa]]s, a group within the [[Bhakti movement]], one of the [[monotheistic]] [[Hindu]] religious [[devotional movements]] focusing on the spiritual practice of loving devotion to a God, called [[bhakti]]. This generally means the worship of [[Shiva]] or [[Vishnu]] or [[Shakti]]. ==History== During the rule of the [[Vijayanagar Empire]] in [[South India]] in the 12th and 13th centuries A.D., the [[Haridasa]] movement spread from the area of modern [[Karnataka]]. The [[Lingayatism]] movement (the term is derived from Lingavantha in [[Kannada]]), spread the philosophy of [[Basavanna]], a Hindu reformer. The [[Vyasakuta]] were required to be proficient in the [[Vedas]], [[Upanishads]] and other [[Darshana]]s.<ref name="dvaita">{{cite web |url=http://www.dvaita.org/haridasa/overview/vdkuta.html |title=What is the meaning of Vysakoota & Dasakoota |publisher=dvaita.org |accessdate=2007-01-16 }}</ref> The role of the Dasakuta was to convey the message of [[Madhvacharya]] through the [[Kannada]] language to the people.
